The file NTUSER.MAN is a binary registry hive placed in a user's profile folder to exploit Windows mandatory user profiles, causing the system to load it instead of the normal NTUSER.DAT at login.

It is malicious because it was crafted offline using the Offline Registry API (offreg.dll) to embed a persistent Run or RunOnce key that executes an attacker‑controlled command each time the user logs in.

This technique bypasses EDR because it never calls live registry APIs (such as RegSetValue), which are the primary hooks for detecting registry modifications; offreg.dll operates directly on the hive file and is rarely monitored.

The only observable artifact is the creation of NTUSER.MAN in the user’s profile directory, making the persistence stealthy and effective even without administrative privileges.

